> Hi Carl,
> Yes, but then it cools down so much especially when idling and hardly
> reaches
> a minimum of 160 oil temp to keep not only the water vapor out of the oil,
> but also keep alot of raw fuel out of the oil!  Plus you get better ring
> longevity and better sealing (= more HP) when up to proper engine temp.
> Lastly your engine does not tear itself slowly apart due to constantly
> changing shape and size due to these large fluctuant engine temps.
